menu "breadboard: bb_mdns"

config BB_MDNS_INSTANCE_NAME_MAX
    int "Maximum mDNS instance name length (bytes, including NUL)"
    default 32
    range 16 64
    help
        Governs BB_MDNS_INSTANCE_NAME_MAX in bb_mdns.h and sizes the
        instance_name field inside bb_mdns_identity_t (and thus
        bb_mdns_peer_t / bb_mdns_query_result_t).  Fleet instance names
        are typically ≤18 chars (e.g. "TaipanMiner-abc123"); the default
        of 32 provides headroom while saving ~32 B per struct slot vs the
        old 64 B default.  Raise to 64 only if your instance names exceed
        31 printable characters.

config BB_MDNS_HOSTNAME_MAX
    int "Maximum mDNS hostname length (bytes, including NUL)"
    default 32
    range 16 64
    help
        Governs BB_MDNS_HOSTNAME_MAX in bb_mdns.h and sizes the hostname
        field inside bb_mdns_identity_t.  Fleet hostnames are typically
        ≤17 chars (e.g. "tdongles3-1.local"); the default of 32 is
        sufficient.  Raise to 64 only if your hostnames exceed 31 chars.

config BB_MDNS_EVT_POOL_SIZE
    int "Notifier event pool size"
    default 8
    range 4 64
    help
        Pre-allocated bb_mdns_evt_t slots used by the notifier callback to
        hand events to the dispatch task without per-event malloc. IDF's
        mDNS task delivers a linked list of mdns_result_t in one callback,
        so this caps how many peers can be queued in a single notify burst
        before events are dropped (logged as "event pool exhausted").

        Each slot is ~588 bytes; default 8 fits 1-8 peers and saves ~4.7 KB
        BSS vs the old default of 16. Raise to 16+ for large LANs.

config BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX
    int "mDNS coalescing batch size (input side)"
    default 16
    range 2 64
    help
        Maximum number of peer events buffered in the in-progress coalescing
        batch (s_batch, one static bb_mdns_evt_t[BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX] array,
        ~516 B per slot, total ~8.2 KB at default of 16) before a synchronous
        flush into the dispatch ring is triggered.

        BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX also determines the size of the heap-allocated
        dispatch scratch item (bb_mdns_batch_item_t, ~sizeof(bb_mdns_evt_t)
        * BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX + 4 B) allocated once in bb_mdns_init.  Memory
        cost scales linearly with this value.

        On no-PSRAM boards set this to 4 (not the default 16) to keep the
        scratch item and ring slots within internal heap budget.  The default
        of 16 targets PSRAM-equipped boards where the ring allocator places
        large items in SPIRAM.

        Lowering this on small-heap boards reclaims BSS and heap at the cost
        of more frequent flushes into the ring — any peers that overflow both
        the batch and the ring within a single burst are dropped.

config BB_MDNS_BATCH_RING_DEPTH
    int "mDNS dispatch ring capacity (bb_queue drop-new)"
    default 4 if SPIRAM
    default 3
    range 1 32
    help
        Capacity of the bb_queue used to queue coalesced mDNS batch items for
        the dispatch task.  Each slot holds one bb_mdns_batch_item_t (one full
        flush worth of peers, sizeof ~= BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX * ~516 B + 4 B).

        Heap cost (SPIRAM-preferred on ESP-IDF, internal heap on no-PSRAM
        boards): capacity × (bb_queue entry metadata (~24 B) +
        sizeof(bb_mdns_batch_item_t)).  At default capacity=4 and
        BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX=16: 4 × (24 + 4 + 16 * 516) ≈ 33 KB on SPIRAM;
        on no-PSRAM boards the same bytes come from internal heap.

        Memory cost scales with BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX — lower both together on
        no-PSRAM boards (e.g. BATCH_MAX=4, RING_DEPTH=3).

        The ring uses BB_QUEUE_REJECT_NEW: when full the 50 ms flush timer
        re-arms and retries the SAME batch on the next tick (the batch is
        not cleared on a failed push).  Raise if your network produces more
        than BB_MDNS_BATCH_RING_DEPTH burst-separated discovery/PTR-scan cycles before
        the dispatch task can drain.

        PSRAM-axis DERIVE (B1-435): default 4 on SPIRAM boards (ring lives
        in SPIRAM; large batches affordable), 3 on no-PSRAM boards (internal
        heap is the bottleneck; aligns with TaipanMiner sdkconfig/no-psram).
        BB_MDNS_BATCH_MAX is left at its flat default of 16 because it is
        set for DIFFERENT reasons by both single-core and no-PSRAM fragments
        in TaipanMiner — deriving it on the SPIRAM axis alone would miss the
        single-core constraint.  RING_DEPTH is purely PSRAM-axis and safe to
        derive here.

config BB_MDNS_TXT_PENDING_MAX
    int "Maximum pending TXT key/value pairs before mDNS starts"
    default 4
    range 1 16
    help
        bb_mdns_set_txt() may be called before the mDNS service has started.
        Pending writes are held in a static table of this size and flushed
        when the service starts. Default 4 covers typical usage (update,
        board, fw, custom key). Raise if more TXT keys are set pre-start.

config BB_MDNS_TASK_PRIORITY
    int "bb_mdns dispatch/query task priority"
    default 3
    range 1 24
    help
        FreeRTOS priority for the bb_mdns dispatch and query tasks. The
        dispatch task drains coalesced browse-notify events and frees the
        single coalescing batch slot; if it is starved the slot is not freed
        in time and bursts of peer events are dropped (logged as
        "notifier: queue+batch full").

        On dual-core boards the default of 3 is ample — the task runs on the
        core the miner is not pinned to. On single-core boards (ESP32-C3/S2)
        the dispatch task competes with the miner on the one core; raise this
        (e.g. 10, still well below a typical priority-20 mining task) so it
        drains promptly and browse-based discovery (e.g. knot) does not lag.
        Keep it below the consumer's mining/hot-loop task priority.

endmenu
